Interview Questions
1) What is the structure of a Java package?
-->A Java package is a hierarchical mechanism used to group related classes, interfaces, and sub-packages into a single unit,
    serving as both a physical organization tool and a namespace. 
    Structure:
    package com.company.project.module;
    
    public class MyClass {
        // class content
    }
  
    Explanation:  
    package → keyword to declare package
    com.company.project.module → hierarchical naming (folders inside folders)
    Each level represents a directory in the file system
    👉 Example folder structure:
    
    com/
     └── company/
          └── project/
               └── module/
                    └── MyClass.class



2) Explain the difference between top-level and sub-packages.
-->
| Feature      | Top-Level Package | Sub-Package                    |
| ------------ | ----------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Definition   | Main package      | Package inside another package |
| Example      | `com`             | `com.company`                  |
| Relationship | Independent root  | Child of another package       |
| Creation     | Created directly  | Created inside another package |



3) What are naming conventions for packages?
-->Java follows standard naming rules:

    Use lowercase letters only
    Use reverse domain name (to avoid conflicts)
    Avoid special characters and spaces
    
    👉 Examples:
    com.google.util
    org.apache.commons
    com.karthikeya.project
    
    ❌ Wrong:  
    MyPackage      // uppercase
    com@project    // special character




4) How does the JVM locate classes inside a package?
-->JVM uses the classpath to locate classes.

    Process:
    
    Package name is converted into folder structure
    com.company.app → com/company/app/
    JVM searches in:
    Current directory
    CLASSPATH environment variable
    JAR files
    Loads .class file into memory
    
    👉 Example:
    
    java -cp . com.company.app.MainClass




5) Explain the difference between .class files in default and user-defined packages.
-->
| Feature             | Default Package                | User-Defined Package        |
| ------------------- | ------------------------------ | --------------------------- |
| Package Declaration | No package statement           | Has `package` statement     |
| Location            | Current directory              | Inside folder structure     |
| Access              | Limited (cannot import easily) | Can be imported anywhere    |
| Organization        | Poor                           | Well-organized              |
| Example             | `MyClass.class`                | `com/company/MyClass.class` |
